The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             
	Montgomery gets 46 months  White Plains: Former US Olympic sprinter Tim Montgomery was sentenced to 46 months in prison on Friday for a cheque fraud and money laundering scheme that also helped bring down Marion Jones, his former girlfriend. The sentencing marked the latest slide for the onetime fastest man in the world, who was already in federal custody on suspicion of conspiracy to possess heroin with intent to distribute in Virginia. He has yet to be tried in that case.  
	Pistorius wins appeal   Lausanne: Double-amputee sprinter Oscar Pistorius has won an appeal to compete for a place in the Beijing Olympics. The Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS) has ruled that the 21-year-old South African is eligible to race against able-bodied athletes. Friday rsquo;s verdict overturns a ban imposed by the IAAF which said his carbon fibre prosthetic blades gave him a mechanical advantage. CAS said the unanimous ruling goes into effect immediately.  
	Chambers rsquo; challenge   London: British sprinter Dwain Chambers will challenge his lifetime Olympic ban for doping in a bid to compete at the Beijing Games. On the day Chambers met with Britain rsquo;s national anti-doping organisation and handed over a letter detailing the drug regimen that led to a two-year suspension, his lawyer said on Friday the runner would seek to compete in the British trials and rescind his lifetime Olympic ban.  
	City get Uefa berth  London: Manchester City will play in next season rsquo;s Uefa Cup after England were awarded an extra spot in the competition for topping Uefa rsquo;s Fair Play table. The Premier League confirmed on Friday that City would be the recipients of the extra spot after it published its own final fair play standings. Though City came only sixth in the fair play table, the five clubs in front of them had already qualified for European competition.  
	Zidane to lead   Sydney: French World Cup star Zinedine Zidane will head an international side set to play an Australian team in a exhibition on June 1 in Sydney. Zidane will lead a team featuring a number of his teammates from the side that won the 1998 World Cup, including Marcel Desailly and Robert Pires, along with Danish international Jesper Olsen.  
	Euro matches live  Calcutta: ESPN STAR Sports has announced that all Euro 2008 matches will be beamed live amp; exclusive in India on ESPN. In all, 31 matches will be played starting from June 7, says A Staff Reporter. The final is in Vienna on June 30.
                                                                                                                                                               
